00:04:00,850 --> 00:04:05,200
<i>The extraordinary story of
'The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy'</i>

18
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:06,950
<i>begins very simply.</i>

19
00:04:07,050 --> 00:04:09,000
<i>It begins with a man.</i>

21
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:20,900
<i>An Earthman, to be precise.</i>

22
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:22,600
<i>Who no more knows his destiny,</i>

23
00:04:22,700 --> 00:04:26,200
<i>than a tea leaf knows the history
of the East India Company.</i>

24
00:04:28,500 --> 00:04:31,300
<i>His name is Arthur Dent.</i>

25
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:34,700
<i>He is a 5'8''-tall ape descendant</i>

26
00:04:34,800 --> 00:04:38,800
<i>and someone is trying to drive
a bypass through his house.</i>

27
00:04:44,100 --> 00:04:46,250
What do I want you to do about it?
Well, I want you to find him

28
00:04:46,350 --> 00:04:50,300
and tell him that I'm currently
lying flat on my back in front of...

29
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:51,700
Fine, I'll hold.

30
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:54,500
Come off it, Mr. Dent. You can't lie
in front of the bulldozers for ever.

31
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:56,700
Well, I'm game. We'll see who rusts first.

32
00:04:56,800 --> 00:05:00,100
This bypass has got to be built
and it is going to be built.

33
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:04,250
- Why has it got to be built?
- It's a bypass!

34
00:05:04,350 --> 00:05:06,000
You've got to build bypasses.

34
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:08,900
Besides, you should've made
your protest months ago.

35
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,350
These plans have been on display
at the planning office now for a year.

36
00:05:12,450 --> 00:05:15,100
On display? I had to go down to a cellar!

37
00:05:15,250 --> 00:05:20,550
Mr. Dent, have you any idea how much
damage this bulldozer would suffer,

38
00:05:20,650 --> 00:05:23,100
if I just let it roll straight over you?

39
00:05:24,300 --> 00:05:27,300
- How much?
- None at all.

40
00:05:27,400 --> 00:05:30,200
<i>By a strange coincidence, none at all</i>

41
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:34,000
<i>is exactly how much suspicion
the ape-descendant Arthur Dent had</i>

42
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:35,850
<i>that one of his closest friends</i>

43
00:05:35,950 --> 00:05:39,600
<i>was not descended from an ape,
but was, in fact, from a small planet</i>

44
00:05:39,700 --> 00:05:43,050
<i>somewhere in the vicinity of Betelgeuse.</i>

45
00:05:43,850 --> 00:05:46,350
Arthur! Arthur!

46
00:05:46,450 --> 00:05:48,200
- Ford!
- Yes?

47
00:05:48,300 --> 00:05:49,750
Here.

48
00:05:49,850 --> 00:05:51,200
Ah, there you are!

49
00:05:51,300 --> 00:05:53,100
Come, eat, drink with me. We gotta talk.

50
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:56,400
Now's not the best time.
They're going to demolish my home.

51
00:05:56,500 --> 00:06:00,950
Whoa! You already...
You already know? How?

52
00:06:01,050 --> 00:06:02,950
What do you m...?

53
00:06:04,700 --> 00:06:07,800
Oh, they, they? When you say "they",
you mean they? Got it.

54
00:06:07,900 --> 00:06:12,550
Listen, I got something important
I gotta tell you. I gotta tell you right now.

55
00:06:12,650 --> 00:06:15,000
Well, what about my house?

56
00:06:19,650 --> 00:06:25,100
Workers of the Earth, I bring
good tidings of peanuts and beer!

57
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:37,500
- Good. Next thing. Come on,
let's go to the pub. - Huh?

58
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:40,600
They said they won't demolish your home
until they've finished the beers.

59
00:06:40,700 --> 00:06:43,100
- Can we trust them?
- I trust them to the end of the Earth.

60
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:45,550
- How far's that?
- About 12 minutes away.

61
00:06:45,650 --> 00:06:46,700
Huh?

62
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:50,750
Barman, six pints of bitter and quickly.
The world's about to end.

63
00:06:50,850 --> 00:06:52,750
Six pints coming up.

64
00:06:52,850 --> 00:06:56,500
Keep the change.
You got about ten minutes to spend it.

65
00:06:56,650 --> 00:06:59,950
Three pints each? At lunchtime?

66
00:07:07,050 --> 00:07:08,100
Sorry.

66
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:11,500
Time is an illusion.

67
00:07:11,600 --> 00:07:13,750
Lunchtime, doubly so.

68
00:07:13,850 --> 00:07:17,650
And eat those peanuts,
because you'll need the salt.

69
00:07:17,750 --> 00:07:20,400
- Look, what is going on, Ford?
- Arthur...

70
00:07:22,550 --> 00:07:26,050
What if I told you
I really wasn't from Guildford?

71
00:07:26,150 --> 00:07:30,550
I was from a small planet somewhere
in the vicinity of Betelgeuse?

72
00:07:30,650 --> 00:07:32,700
Is that something you're likely to say?

73
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:34,150
Remember when we met?

74
00:07:41,200 --> 00:07:42,300
Get out the way!

75
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,000
Hi.

76
00:07:47,100 --> 00:07:50,100
Do you think it was a bit strange
I was trying to shake hands with a car?

77
00:07:50,200 --> 00:07:51,750
I assumed you were drunk.

78
00:07:51,850 --> 00:07:55,900
I thought cars were the dominant life form.
I was trying to introducing myself.

79
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,450
You saved my life that day, and now
I'm saving yours. Please drink.

80
00:08:00,550 --> 00:08:03,100
It must be Thursday. I could never
get the hang of Thursdays.

81
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:07,350
- Arthur, if this is about your house--
- No, it's not about the house.

82
00:08:11,350 --> 00:08:13,400
- Who's he?
- She. She!

83
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:17,150
Tricia McMillan.
We met at a fancy-dress party.

84
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:20,650
<i>See, I hate those kind of parties.</i>

85
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:23,800
<i>I'd much rather have stayed at home
and, I don't know, ironed my hankies.</i>

86
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:25,900
- <i>But anyway, there I was.</i>
- Who are you?

87
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,700
- Oh!
- <i>And there she was.</i>

88
00:08:27,800 --> 00:08:32,550
- Dent. Arthur Dent.
- Oh, no. I mean, who are you?

89
00:08:32,650 --> 00:08:35,900
Oh, the costume? Right.
"Livingstone, I presume!"

90
00:08:37,050 --> 00:08:41,350
Yeah, it's not as clever as Darwin, I know,
but it's the best I could do at short notice.

91
00:08:41,450 --> 00:08:43,500
You're the first preson who's done that right.

92
00:08:43,600 --> 00:08:44,600
- Really?
- Yes.

92
00:08:44,700 --> 00:08:46,400
Everyone keeps calling me Santa.

93
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:47,500
Right.

93
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:49,000
And I thought the beagle made it
a dead giveaway.

94
00:08:49,100 --> 00:08:50,600
Yes! Well, so did I.

95
00:08:50,700 --> 00:08:53,200
I guess most of the people who come
to these sort of parties are drunken idiots.

96
00:08:53,300 --> 00:08:54,400
What?

97
00:08:54,500 --> 00:08:58,500
I said, all these people are idiots! God!

98
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:02,950
That's awkward.

99
00:09:03,050 --> 00:09:04,850
Tell me.

100
00:09:06,750 --> 00:09:09,550
She was amazing though, Ford.

101
00:09:09,650 --> 00:09:12,600
<i>Beautiful, witty, mad as a balloon.</i>

102
00:09:12,700 --> 00:09:17,350
I've got to say, without the beard,
you look at least 80 years younger.

103
00:09:17,450 --> 00:09:20,150
Maybe I'm de-evolving.

104
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:24,300
Well, I feel should tell you

105
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:28,650
that I do not date single-celled organisms,
okay?

106
00:09:31,350 --> 00:09:33,500
Let's go somewhere.

107
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:35,000
Yeah, definitely.

107
00:09:36,500 --> 00:09:37,750
Where do you have in mind?

108
00:09:37,850 --> 00:09:41,800
- Madagascar.
- Is that that new club on Dean Street?

109
00:09:41,900 --> 00:09:45,250
No, it's a country off the coast of Africa.

110
00:09:45,350 --> 00:09:48,300
That Madagascar?!
Why are we waiting here?

111
00:09:48,900 --> 00:09:51,000
Wait a sec.

112
00:09:51,500 --> 00:09:53,050
Go!

113
00:09:56,200 --> 00:09:57,500
God, you're serious.

113
00:09:59,500 --> 00:10:00,700
I can't go to Madagascar.

114
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:03,800
- Why not?
- Well, because, I just, you know...

115
00:10:03,900 --> 00:10:05,300
- You're really serious?
- Yeah.

116
00:10:05,400 --> 00:10:09,000
I want to go somewhere I've never been
and I'd like to go with you, so...

117
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:11,500
What do you say, Dr Livingstone?

118
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:17,750
I say that's an extraordinary proposition.

119
00:10:17,850 --> 00:10:20,850
I can't go. I mean, I've got a job.

120
00:10:20,950 --> 00:10:23,200
Quit. Get a new one when you come back.

121
00:10:23,300 --> 00:10:25,000
I don't even know your real name.

122
00:10:25,400 --> 00:10:28,700
- Tricia McMillan.
- Well, Tricia McMillan.

123
00:10:29,800 --> 00:10:32,250
I have a proposition for you.

124
00:10:32,350 --> 00:10:39,200
Why don't we go somewhere
a little closer first, say Cornwall,

125
00:10:39,300 --> 00:10:43,000
and we'll see how it goes.

126
00:10:43,350 --> 00:10:47,850
Right, of course, Cornwall.

127
00:10:47,950 --> 00:10:50,200
Hey, excuse me.

128
00:10:53,100 --> 00:10:54,550
Is this guy boring you?

129
00:10:54,650 --> 00:10:57,200
Why don't you talk to me instead?

130
00:10:57,300 --> 00:11:00,600
I'm from a different planet.

131
00:11:03,300 --> 00:11:06,450
It's true. You want to see my spaceship?

132
00:11:07,950 --> 00:11:11,600
"Do you want to see my spaceship?"
I mean, really, what kind of chat-up line is that?

133
00:11:11,700 --> 00:11:14,850
Mmm, that does happen.

134
00:11:14,950 --> 00:11:17,500
Speaking of...

135
00:11:18,050 --> 00:11:20,300
We've got two minutes.
Drink up, drink up, drink up.

136
00:11:20,400 --> 00:11:22,350
That's my house!

137
00:11:30,150 --> 00:11:34,200
People of Earth, a round of drinks,
for everyone on me.

138
00:11:34,300 --> 00:11:36,950
Do you really think the world's going to end?

139
00:11:37,050 --> 00:11:38,550
Yes.

140
00:11:38,650 --> 00:11:43,100
Shouldn't we lie down, or put a paper
bag over our heads, or something?

141
00:11:43,200 --> 00:11:46,100
- If you like.
- Will it help?

142
00:11:46,200 --> 00:11:48,900
Not at all. See you.

143
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,200
Last order today!

144
00:12:06,600 --> 00:12:08,850
- What is that?!
- Run!

145
00:12:08,950 --> 00:12:10,900
Look out!

146
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:39,750
A-ha! Towel!

147
00:12:41,850 --> 00:12:43,800
Arthur!

148
00:12:43,900 --> 00:12:45,900
What the hell are those things?

149
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,500
They're ships from a Vogon constructor fleet.

150
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:52,800
I picked up their signal this morning.
Here, you'll need this.

151
00:12:54,250 --> 00:12:57,400
- What are you doing?
- Hang on, we're hitching a ride.

152
00:13:00,650 --> 00:13:02,200
People of Earth,

153
00:13:02,350 --> 00:13:07,750
this is Prostetnic Vogon Jeltz of the
Galactic Hyperspace Planning Council.

154
00:13:07,850 --> 00:13:09,400
As you are probably aware,

155
00:13:09,500 --> 00:13:13,000
<i>plans for the development of
the outlying regions of the galaxy</i>

156
00:13:13,100 --> 00:13:17,750
involve the building of a hyperspace
express route through your star system.

157
00:13:17,850 --> 00:13:22,000
And your planet is one of those
scheduled for demolition.

158
00:13:30,050 --> 00:13:32,550
<i>There's no point acting
all surprised about it.</i>

159
00:13:32,650 --> 00:13:35,150
<i>The plans and demolition orders
have been on display</i>

160
00:13:35,250 --> 00:13:39,000
<i>at your local planning office
in Alpha Centauri for 50 of your Earth years.</i>

161
00:13:40,150 --> 00:13:43,850
<i>If you can't be bothered to take any interest
in your local affairs, that's your own lookout.</i>

162
00:13:43,950 --> 00:13:46,350
Apathetic bloody planet.

163
00:13:46,450 --> 00:13:49,200
I've no sympathy at all.

164
00:15:36,900 --> 00:15:39,900
<i>'The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy'</i>

165
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:42,150
<i>is a wholly remarkable book.</i>

166
00:15:42,250 --> 00:15:45,500
<i>Perhaps the most remarkable,
certainly the most successful book,</i>

167
00:15:45,600 --> 00:15:49,650
<i>ever to come out of the great publishing
corporations of Ursa Minor.</i>

168
00:15:49,750 --> 00:15:53,050
<i>More popular than
'The Celestial Homecare Omnibus',</i>

169
00:15:53,150 --> 00:15:56,950
<i>better selling than
'53 More Things to Do in Zero Gravity',</i>

170
00:15:57,050 --> 00:16:00,000
<i>and more controversial than
Oolon Colluphid's trilogy</i>

171
00:16:00,100 --> 00:16:03,250
<i>of philosophical blockbusters,
'Where God Went Wrong',</i>

172
00:16:03,400 --> 00:16:05,850
'Some More of God's Greatest Mistakes',

173
00:16:05,950 --> 00:16:08,300
<i>and 'Who Is This God Person Anyway?'</i>

174
00:16:09,150 --> 00:16:12,100
<i>It's already supplanted
the 'Encyclopedia Galactica'</i>

175
00:16:12,200 --> 00:16:15,100
<i>as the standard repository
of all knowledge and wisdom</i>

176
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:17,800
<i>for two important reasons.</i>

177
00:16:17,900 --> 00:16:20,500
<i>First, it's slightly cheaper,</i>

178
00:16:20,600 --> 00:16:23,650
<i>and second, it has the words "Don't Panic"</i>

179
00:16:23,750 --> 00:16:27,250
<i>printed in large, friendly letters on its cover.</i>

180
00:16:35,900 --> 00:16:38,700
So you're not from Guildford.

181
00:16:38,800 --> 00:16:42,850
Which would explain the accent,
which I've always wondered about.

182
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:46,700
You're not an out-of-work actor,

183
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:52,250
but rather a writer for this... this book thing.

184
00:16:52,350 --> 00:16:54,750
It's good, huh?

185
00:16:54,850 --> 00:16:57,250
I don't feel well. I need a cup of tea.

186
00:16:57,350 --> 00:17:00,750
If I asked where we were, would I regret it?

187
00:17:00,850 --> 00:17:04,100
- We're safe for now.
- Good.

188
00:17:04,200 --> 00:17:08,050
We're in the washroom on one of the
ships of the Vogon constructor fleet.

189
00:17:08,150 --> 00:17:11,650
- Oh, get me home, Ford!
- Arthur, your home is...

190
00:17:11,750 --> 00:17:16,300
Oh, God, my home!
My home was demolished.

191
00:17:21,200 --> 00:17:23,050
You don't remember.

192
00:17:24,150 --> 00:17:30,450
Okay, Arthur, I've got something to tell you.
It's unfortunate, but it's true.

193
00:17:30,550 --> 00:17:33,750
Your home planet has been blown up.

194
00:17:42,600 --> 00:17:46,000
Blown up!

195
00:17:51,500 --> 00:17:53,500
Couldn't you have done something?

196
00:17:53,600 --> 00:17:57,500
I saved your life.
Okay, that makes us even.

197
00:17:57,600 --> 00:18:01,650
It's a tough galaxy. If you want
to survive out here, you've...

198
00:18:01,750 --> 00:18:05,350
gotta know where your towel is.

199
00:18:05,450 --> 00:18:08,000
Okay, give me a hand over here.

200
00:18:10,450 --> 00:18:14,300
Careful. It's hot.
We've gotta get off this ship.

201
00:18:14,400 --> 00:18:16,600
Before the Vogons find us.

202
00:18:16,700 --> 00:18:19,750
Vogons, they hate hitchhikers. Pull.

204
00:18:25,550 --> 00:18:28,900
- Now we'll get a signal.
- What is a Vogon?

205
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:30,800
Ask the Guide. Say "Vogons".

206
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:34,650
Vogons.

207
00:18:35,450 --> 00:18:39,850
<i>Vogons are one of the most
unpleasant races in the galaxy.</i>

208
00:18:39,950 --> 00:18:44,250
<i>Not evil, but bad-tempered,
bureaucratic, officious and callous.</i>

209
00:18:44,350 --> 00:18:47,850
<i>They wouldn't even lift a finger
to save their own grandmothers</i>

210
00:18:47,950 --> 00:18:51,200
<i>from the Ravenous Bugblatter
Beast of Traal without orders</i>

211
00:18:51,300 --> 00:18:53,700
<i>signed in triplicate, sent in, sent back,</i>

212
00:18:53,800 --> 00:18:57,150
<i>queried, lost, found,
subjected to public inquiry,</i>

213
00:18:57,300 --> 00:19:00,650
<i>lost again and finally buried
in soft peat for three months</i>

214
00:19:00,750 --> 00:19:03,600
<i>and recycled as firelighters.</i>

215
00:19:04,950 --> 00:19:09,750
<i>On no account should you allow
a Vogon to read poetry to you.</i>

216
00:19:11,350 --> 00:19:15,950
They can't think, they can't imagine. Most of
them can't even spell. They just run things.

217
00:19:19,100 --> 00:19:20,650
Hmm?

218
00:19:22,300 --> 00:19:24,250
And if we don't get a ride soon,

219
00:19:24,400 --> 00:19:27,750
we won't need the Guide to tell us
just how unpleasant the Vogons can be.

220
00:19:27,850 --> 00:19:30,200
They've already destroyed a planet today.

221
00:19:30,300 --> 00:19:32,600
That always makes them a little <i>eee</i>!

222
00:19:38,500 --> 00:19:39,650
What is that?

223
00:19:39,750 --> 00:19:41,000
Put this in your ear.

223
00:19:42,500 --> 00:19:44,000
Huh? Ford!

224
00:19:46,550 --> 00:19:50,400
<i>We have unwittingly picked up
a couple of hitchhikers.</i>

225
00:19:50,500 --> 00:19:53,000
The fish is translating for you.

226
00:19:54,200 --> 00:19:57,300
<i>The Babel fish is small, yellow, leech-like,</i>

227
00:19:57,400 --> 00:20:01,700
<i>and probably the oddest thing
in the universe.</i>

228
00:20:01,800 --> 00:20:06,250
<i>It feeds on brainwave energy,
absorbing unconscious frequencies,</i>

229
00:20:06,350 --> 00:20:08,900
<i>and excreting a matrix
of conscious frequencies</i>

230
00:20:09,050 --> 00:20:11,250
<i>to the speech centers of the brain.</i>

231
00:20:11,350 --> 00:20:14,850
<i>The practical upshot of which is that,
if you stick one in your ear,</i>

232
00:20:14,950 --> 00:20:20,550
<i>you instantly understand
anything said to you in any language.</i>

233
00:20:28,700 --> 00:20:31,150
Resistance is useless.

234
00:20:34,500 --> 00:20:37,050
- All right.
- Someone's coming.

235
00:20:37,150 --> 00:20:39,550
Here we go. Look lively.

238
00:21:16,850 --> 00:21:18,550
Sir?

239
00:21:18,650 --> 00:21:21,400
- What?
- Hitchhikers.

240
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:04,000
"O freddled gruntbuggly..."

241
00:22:04,100 --> 00:22:06,650
Oh, no, no, really.
Really you don't have to read.

242
00:22:06,750 --> 00:22:09,400
We've put you through
enough trouble already.

243
00:22:09,500 --> 00:22:14,700
"... as plerdled gabbleblotchits
on a lurgid bee."

244
00:22:14,800 --> 00:22:20,150
<i>Vogon poetry is widely accepted
as the third worst in the universe.</i>

245
00:22:21,300 --> 00:22:24,550
<i>The second worst
is that of the Azgoths of Kria.</i>

246
00:22:24,650 --> 00:22:28,200
<i>During a recitation by their Poet Master,
Grunthos the Flatulent,</i>

247
00:22:28,300 --> 00:22:31,200
<i>of his poem
'Ode to a Small Lump of Green Putty</i>

248
00:22:31,300 --> 00:22:33,850
'I Found in my Armpit
One Midsummer Morning',

249
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,200
<i>four of his audience
died of internal hemorrhaging,</i>

250
00:22:37,300 --> 00:22:40,700
<i>and the President of the
Mid-Galactic Arts Nobbling Council</i>

251
00:22:40,800 --> 00:22:43,300
<i>survived by gnawing
one of his own legs off.</i>

252
00:22:43,400 --> 00:22:48,300
"Or I will rend thee in the gobberwarts"

253
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:51,350
"with my blurgle..."

254
00:22:51,450 --> 00:22:55,800
<i>The absolute worst poetry was written
by Paula Nancy Millstone Jennings of Sussex.</i>

255
00:22:55,900 --> 00:22:58,450
<i>Luckily, it was destroyed
when the Earth was.</i>

256
00:22:58,550 --> 00:23:03,200
"See if I don't." Yeah.

257
00:23:05,400 --> 00:23:10,750
So, Earthlings, I present you with a choice.

258
00:23:10,850 --> 00:23:14,000
Either die in the vacuum of space,

259
00:23:14,100 --> 00:23:18,900
or tell me what you thought of my poem.

260
00:23:20,500 --> 00:23:24,450
Actually, I rather liked it.

261
00:23:24,600 --> 00:23:26,550
- Hmm?
- Yeah.

262
00:23:26,650 --> 00:23:29,350
That's good. That's good, Arthur. Run with it.

263
00:23:29,450 --> 00:23:31,850
Some of the words I didn't understand,

264
00:23:31,950 --> 00:23:35,350
but I found the imagery quite effective.

265
00:23:36,250 --> 00:23:37,550
Continue.

266
00:23:37,650 --> 00:23:41,350
Well, yes, interesting rhythmic devices,

267
00:23:41,450 --> 00:23:43,850
which seemed to counterpoint

268
00:23:43,950 --> 00:23:46,650
the underlying metaphor of the humanity of...

269
00:23:46,750 --> 00:23:49,950
- Vogonity!
- Vogonity, sorry, vogonity.

270
00:23:50,050 --> 00:23:52,400
...of the poet's soul.

271
00:23:56,100 --> 00:24:00,200
So, what you're saying is,

272
00:24:00,300 --> 00:24:02,900
I write poetry, because

273
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:07,350
underneath this mean,
callous, heartless exterior,

274
00:24:07,450 --> 00:24:11,400
I just want to be loved?

275
00:24:12,750 --> 00:24:14,750
Yes, yes, yes.

276
00:24:14,850 --> 00:24:17,250
Yes, yes, yeah, please.

278
00:24:22,950 --> 00:24:24,500
Throw them off the ship!

281
00:24:29,650 --> 00:24:31,900
All right! All right!

282
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:35,550
Resistance is useless!

283
00:24:38,250 --> 00:24:42,750
Shut up! Get a job! Wash your filthy hands!

284
00:24:42,850 --> 00:24:45,550
Don't panic. Don't panic.

285
00:24:45,650 --> 00:24:51,650
So this is it. We're gonna die.

286
00:24:51,750 --> 00:24:55,350
Yeah, we're gonna die.

287
00:24:55,500 --> 00:24:58,400
No, no, what's this?

288
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:00,100
- What's that?
- What's this?

289
00:25:00,200 --> 00:25:04,550
What's this? This is nothing.
Yeah, we're gonna die.

290
00:25:15,200 --> 00:25:17,300
You're sweating.

291
00:25:25,550 --> 00:25:27,850
- Would you like a hug?
- No.

292
00:25:41,350 --> 00:25:44,950
<i>"Space", says the introduction
to 'The Hitchhiker's Guide',</i>

293
00:25:45,050 --> 00:25:47,500
<i>"is big. Really big.</i>

294
00:25:47,600 --> 00:25:52,950
<i>"You just won't believe how vastly,
hugely, mind-bogglingly big it is."</i>

295
00:25:53,050 --> 00:25:54,950
<i>And so on.</i>

296
00:25:55,050 --> 00:25:58,100
<i>It also says that if you hold a lungful of air,</i>

297
00:25:58,200 --> 00:26:03,600
<i>you can survive in the total vacuum
of space for about 30 seconds.</i>

298
00:26:03,700 --> 00:26:05,850
<i>But with space being really big and all,</i>

299
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:08,500
<i>the chances of being picked up
within that time</i>

300
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:10,800
<i>are two to the power of two billion,</i>

301
00:26:10,900 --> 00:26:13,900
<i>79 million, 460 thousand,</i>

302
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:17,000
<i>347 to one against.</i>

303
00:26:17,100 --> 00:26:18,850
<i>Which, by a staggering coincidence,</i>

304
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,600
<i>is also the telephone number
of the Islington flat,</i>

305
00:26:21,700 --> 00:26:23,900
<i>where Arthur went to a fancy dress party</i>

306
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:27,350
<i>and met a very nice young woman
whom he totally blew it with.</i>

307
00:26:30,850 --> 00:26:34,850
<i>Though the planet Earth,
the Islington flat and telephone</i>

308
00:26:34,950 --> 00:26:40,600
<i>have all now been demolished,
Ford and Arthur were, in fact, rescued.</i>

309
00:26:40,700 --> 00:26:43,500
- Ford?
- Yes.

310
00:26:43,600 --> 00:26:47,700
- I think I'm a sofa.
- I know how you feel.

311
00:26:55,150 --> 00:26:57,850
So much for the laws of physics.

312
00:26:57,950 --> 00:26:59,750
<i>And once again our top story.</i>

313
00:26:59,850 --> 00:27:04,150
<i>The sensational theft of the most
coveted ship in the universe,</i>

314
00:27:04,250 --> 00:27:06,150
<i>the starship Heart of Gold.</i>

315
00:27:06,250 --> 00:27:08,750
<i>Stolen at the launch ceremony
by none other</i>

316
00:27:08,900 --> 00:27:11,700
<i>than Galactic President
Zaphod Beeblebrox.</i>

317
00:27:11,800 --> 00:27:17,050
<i>In the name of people, freedom,
and democracy, stuff like that,</i>

318
00:27:17,150 --> 00:27:21,000
<i>I hereby kidnap myself
and I'm taking the ship with me.</i>

319
00:27:21,300 --> 00:27:23,300
<i>Come on!</i>

320
00:27:23,400 --> 00:27:25,850
<i>Beeblebrox, universally considered</i>

321
00:27:25,950 --> 00:27:28,950
<i>to be the dimmest star
in several solar systems,</i>

322
00:27:29,050 --> 00:27:32,700
<i>is most famous for his controversial
defeat of Humma Kavula,</i>

323
00:27:32,800 --> 00:27:36,750
<i>who claimed many thought they were voting
for the worst-dressed sentient being</i>

324
00:27:36,850 --> 00:27:39,850
<i>in the universe contest.</i>

325
00:27:39,950 --> 00:27:41,000
Great.

326
00:27:41,100 --> 00:27:44,000
<i>Humma Kavula is, of course,
best remembered for his slanderous</i>

327
00:27:44,100 --> 00:27:46,700
<i>"Don't Vote for Stupid!" campaign.</i>

328
00:27:46,800 --> 00:27:50,250
Can we put your ego aside for a minute?
Something important has happened.

329
00:27:50,350 --> 00:27:52,400
If there's anything more important
than my ego on this ship,

329
00:27:52,500 --> 00:27:54,600
I want it caught and shot right now.

330
00:27:54,700 --> 00:27:56,500
Hey, come on, I love it.

331
00:27:56,600 --> 00:27:59,650
<i>Zaphod's just this guy, you know.</i>

332
00:28:01,100 --> 00:28:04,900
Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey. What d'you...?
I was just watching myself.

333
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:07,950
The computer says we have a couple
of hitchhikers in our receiving bay.

334
00:28:08,050 --> 00:28:10,600
Hitchhikers? Why'd you pick up hitchhikers?

335
00:28:10,700 --> 00:28:12,600
I didn't. The ship did.

336
00:28:12,700 --> 00:28:14,950
What? Say what?

337
00:28:15,050 --> 00:28:18,000
When we engaged the Improbability Drive...

338
00:28:18,300 --> 00:28:20,200
- This? The big button?
- Yeah, I know.

339
00:28:20,300 --> 00:28:23,000
They were picked up here
in sector ZZ9 Plural Z Alpha.

339
00:28:23,100 --> 00:28:25,900
Wait a minite. That's where you picked me up.

340
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:27,000
- What?
- On Earth.

340
00:28:27,100 --> 00:28:28,200
- That's impossible.
- No.

341
00:28:28,300 --> 00:28:30,000
- Just very improbable.
- Listen, Slam.

341
00:28:30,100 --> 00:28:31,600
I don't have time for this, you know?

342
00:28:31,700 --> 00:28:33,700
We've got the police of half the galaxy after us.

342
00:28:33,800 --> 00:28:36,000
We've stopped to pick up hitchhikers. Okay!

343
00:28:36,100 --> 00:28:38,450
So ten out of ten for style, but...

344
00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:40,950
minus several million for good thinking.

345
00:28:41,050 --> 00:28:44,350
You're too gorgeous, baby.
Stop it. You drive me crazy.

346
00:28:45,450 --> 00:28:47,800
Don't. I'll send Marvin.

347
00:28:49,100 --> 00:28:50,800
Marvin!

348
00:28:53,950 --> 00:28:56,900
I think you ought to know
I'm feeling very depressed.

349
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:01,350
Well, we have something that
should take your mind off things.

350
00:29:01,450 --> 00:29:06,150
It won't work.
I have an exceptionally large mind.

351
00:29:06,250 --> 00:29:12,150
Yeah, we know. But we need you to go
down to the number two entry bay

352
00:29:12,250 --> 00:29:15,100
and pick up our stowaways
and bring them up here.

353
00:29:15,200 --> 00:29:18,500
Just that? I won't enjoy it.

354
00:29:18,600 --> 00:29:21,200
Yeah, well, that's life.

355
00:29:21,300 --> 00:29:25,550
Life? Don't talk to me about life.

356
00:29:34,750 --> 00:29:37,200
- <i>Commander Kwaltz.</i>
- Yes?

357
00:29:37,300 --> 00:29:41,600
<i>We have located the spaceship
Heart of Gold and President Beeblebrox.</i>

358
00:29:41,700 --> 00:29:45,850
- Where?
- <i>Sector ZZ9 Plural Z Alpha.</i>

359
00:29:45,950 --> 00:29:48,450
<i>Requesting hyperspace clearance.</i>

360
00:29:48,550 --> 00:29:54,500
Hold your position, captain,
until clearance is granted.

361
00:29:54,600 --> 00:30:00,000
- <i>Yes, sir.</i>
- Get me Vice-President Questular.

362
00:30:02,250 --> 00:30:06,500
<i>Hyperspace permission granted, captain.</i>

363
00:30:06,600 --> 00:30:08,950
Here we go.

364
00:30:30,550 --> 00:30:33,250
I think that door just sighed.

365
00:30:33,350 --> 00:30:35,800
Ghastly, isn't it?

366
00:30:35,900 --> 00:30:38,250
All the doors in this spaceship
have been programmed

367
00:30:38,350 --> 00:30:41,600
to have a cheerful and sunny disposition.

368
00:30:43,750 --> 00:30:48,550
Anyway, come on. I've been ordered
to take you up to the bridge.

369
00:30:50,400 --> 00:30:52,350
Please yourselves.

370
00:30:52,450 --> 00:30:55,650
Here I am, brain the size of a planet,

371
00:30:55,750 --> 00:30:58,350
and they ask me to take you up to the bridge.

372
00:30:58,450 --> 00:31:01,700
Call that job satisfaction? 'Cause I don't.

373
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:07,000
You can thank the Sirius Cybernetics
Corp. for building robots with G.P.P.

374
00:31:07,100 --> 00:31:11,300
- What's G.P.P.?
- Genuine People Personalities.

375
00:31:11,450 --> 00:31:15,850
I'm a personality prototype.
You can tell, can't you?

376
00:31:21,750 --> 00:31:23,550
Arthur?

377
00:31:24,450 --> 00:31:29,000
<i>Hey, Slim, are you wearing my underwear?
'Cause I'm wearing yours.</i>

378
00:31:29,100 --> 00:31:31,900
<i>And they ain't doing the trick.
Come on. All right!</i>

379
00:31:33,950 --> 00:31:38,050
Oh, for heaven's sake.

380
00:31:38,150 --> 00:31:41,000
I've brought the aliens.
Don't thank me or anything.

382
00:31:43,300 --> 00:31:45,350
Freeze!

383
00:31:45,450 --> 00:31:48,950
Freeze? I'm a robot. Not a refrigerator.

384
00:31:49,050 --> 00:31:52,650
- I wasn't talking to you, Giggles.
- Oh, why do I bother?

385
00:31:52,750 --> 00:31:54,500
- Zaphod?
- Ford?!

386
00:31:54,650 --> 00:31:59,050
Is that you? Ford! Praxibetel Ix!

387
00:31:59,150 --> 00:32:01,150
What the hell are you doing here?

388
00:32:01,250 --> 00:32:04,650
I don't know. I just stuck out
my thumb and here I am.

389
00:32:04,750 --> 00:32:07,550
- That is so you!
- Look at you!

390
00:32:07,700 --> 00:32:12,050
President of the Galaxy!
I can't believe you beat Humma Kavula.

391
00:32:12,150 --> 00:32:13,800
- You zarkin' frood.
- Hey, come here, come here.

392
00:32:13,900 --> 00:32:18,300
I want you to meet a friend.
Arthur, this is Zaphod Beeblebrox.

393
00:32:18,400 --> 00:32:19,400
Oh!

394
00:32:19,500 --> 00:32:24,450
President of the Galaxy. This is my
cousin. He's a semi-half brother...

395
00:32:24,550 --> 00:32:28,150
- He shares three of the same mothers as me.
- We've met.

396
00:32:28,250 --> 00:32:29,400
- Have we?
- Yeah.

396
00:32:29,600 --> 00:32:33,700
I'm sorry. I've got a terrible
memory for species.

397
00:32:33,800 --> 00:32:38,100
This is him, Ford. The would-you-
like-to-see-my-spaceship bloke.

399
00:32:39,700 --> 00:32:44,950
- Hello, Arthur.
- Tricia!

400
00:32:45,050 --> 00:32:47,400
- How you doin'?
- Hey, Trillian!

401
00:32:47,500 --> 00:32:51,300
This is my semi-half-brother Ix,
I'm sorry, Ford.

402
00:32:51,400 --> 00:32:54,000
- Hi.
- Hi.

403
00:32:54,300 --> 00:32:58,250
Would you excuse us for a second, please?

404
00:32:58,350 --> 00:33:01,600
You went down on that little planet
and didn't even call me?

405
00:33:01,700 --> 00:33:04,500
Sorry, pal, I didn't know.
You know, I had a galaxy to run.

406
00:33:04,600 --> 00:33:06,850
Hi, Tricia McMillan, right?

407
00:33:06,950 --> 00:33:10,150
I think I heard him call you Trillian.
Which of us got the right one?

408
00:33:10,250 --> 00:33:12,750
Oh, I shortened it.
Something a little more spacey.

409
00:33:12,900 --> 00:33:15,450
Right. Yes, well... Actually
I was thinking of changing mine to,

410
00:33:15,550 --> 00:33:17,300
I don't know, Arthoolia.

411
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:21,650
That's a good one!
Well, this is weird.

412
00:33:21,750 --> 00:33:25,250
- How'd you get here?
- I just stuck out my thumb, here I am.

413
00:33:25,350 --> 00:33:29,000
- Right. In your pajamas?
- I was in a hurry.

414
00:33:29,100 --> 00:33:31,150
Okay. Did you know I was here?

415
00:33:31,250 --> 00:33:33,950
Don't flatter yourself.
I've got a spaceman too.

416
00:33:34,100 --> 00:33:36,750
Yeah, that's kinda like the Dingo Shuffle, yeah.

417
00:33:36,850 --> 00:33:38,900
Okay, look...

418
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:42,850
I left you at the party. I feel bad about it,
but I was gonna call you when I got back.

419
00:33:42,950 --> 00:33:45,900
Well, there is no going back now, is there?

420
00:33:47,050 --> 00:33:48,600
You do know what happened, don't you?

421
00:33:48,700 --> 00:33:51,500
Hey, enough small talk. Tria, we're
on the run, remember? I stole a ship.

422
00:33:51,600 --> 00:33:53,500
Excuse me, mate, we're in the middle
of a chat here. Do you mind?

423
00:33:53,650 --> 00:33:56,100
Well, I think the girl's getting... Boo!

424
00:33:56,500 --> 00:34:01,450
You blew it with her, Earthman, so
shut your face or I'll kick you in the zatch.

425
00:34:01,500 --> 00:34:03,150
- You wanna fight? You wanna fight?
- Yeah, okay.

426
00:34:03,250 --> 00:34:04,400
- No, no.
- Earthman wants to fight.

426
00:34:04,500 --> 00:34:06,000
- No.
- I'm just kidding.

427
00:34:06,100 --> 00:34:09,550
I'm a kidder. Come on. Let's be friends.
Let's connect. You and I.

428
00:34:10,450 --> 00:34:12,350
Didn't see that one coming, did you?

429
00:34:12,450 --> 00:34:15,950
Popped right out of the box.
You foxy, yeah!

430
00:34:16,300 --> 00:34:19,500
You should teach your pal a lesson, Ford.
He's a guest on my ship.

431
00:34:19,650 --> 00:34:21,950
He's a guest on my ship!

432
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:25,000
I thought you said you stole it.

433
00:34:26,700 --> 00:34:28,500
Stole what? What are we talking about?

434
00:34:31,600 --> 00:34:33,300
Uh-oh! That doesn't sound good.

435
00:34:37,750 --> 00:34:40,900
- Are you okay?
- Yeah, just fabulous, thanks, Trill.

436
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:44,000
Hey, baby, a little help over here.
I think I'm in over my head.

437
00:34:44,100 --> 00:34:47,450
I'll take care of this. Good Zarquon,
do I have to do everything?

438
00:34:47,550 --> 00:34:48,800
Yes, I do!

439
00:34:48,900 --> 00:34:51,050
Hey, hey, Slim, this is really pretty.

440
00:34:51,150 --> 00:34:53,750
- Don't!
- They're on our tail.

441
00:34:53,850 --> 00:34:56,200
Fire a gun! Launch a missile!
Do some damage!

442
00:35:05,200 --> 00:35:06,750
Ow! Stop that! Ow!

443
00:35:06,900 --> 00:35:08,900
Just kiddin'. I love it rough.
Hit me! Hit me, baby!

444
00:35:09,500 --> 00:35:11,900
- Computer?
- <i>Hi, there.</i>

445
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:14,000
<i>I'm Eddie, your ship-board computer.</i>

446
00:35:14,100 --> 00:35:17,950
<i>I'm just pleased as punch to report that
it's a fleet of a hundred Vogon battle destroyers.</i>

447
00:35:18,050 --> 00:35:20,300
<i>They're sending you a message.</i>

448
00:35:20,400 --> 00:35:22,750
<i>This is Vice-President Questular Rontok.</i>

449
00:35:22,850 --> 00:35:26,250
<i>I am speaking to the kidnapper
of the President?</i>

450
00:35:26,350 --> 00:35:27,550
She digs me. Check it out.

451
00:35:27,650 --> 00:35:29,850
<i>Surrender the stolen vessel at once,</i>

452
00:35:29,950 --> 00:35:35,000
<i>or we will take action
as defined and permitted by...</i>

453
00:35:35,500 --> 00:35:39,400
<i>section 1-8 of the Galactic
Interstellar Space Bylaws...</i>

454
00:35:39,550 --> 00:35:42,900
<i>Zaphod, please come back now.
This is ridiculous.</i>

455
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:45,750
Leap to hyperspace! Come on!

456
00:35:45,850 --> 00:35:48,000
<i>Oh, sure thing, fella!</i>

457
00:35:55,050 --> 00:35:56,450
No!

458
00:35:56,600 --> 00:36:02,000
Did they have proper
hyperspace authorization?

459
00:36:02,100 --> 00:36:05,900
- No, commander!
- Oh.

460
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:11,400
Bring me the request
to pursue fugitive forms.

461
00:36:11,500 --> 00:36:13,500
I'm coming, sir.

462
00:36:16,050 --> 00:36:20,000
I'm boiling! Here's the form, sir.

463
00:36:21,850 --> 00:36:26,100
So, are you along for the ride,
or am I just dropping you somewhere?

464
00:36:26,200 --> 00:36:29,550
That depends. Where are you going?

465
00:36:29,650 --> 00:36:31,650
Where am I going?

466
00:36:32,700 --> 00:36:33,900
- You okay?
- Yeah.

466
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:37,150
Don't suppose there's any tea
in this spaceship, is it?

467
00:36:37,300 --> 00:36:40,350
Yes, there is. Come on.
I'll show you the kitchen.

468
00:36:40,450 --> 00:36:44,900
When you see what I'm about to show you,
you'll beg me to take you with us.

469
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:49,400
<i>The best drink in existence
is the Pan-Galactic Gargle Blaster,</i>

470
00:36:49,500 --> 00:36:54,200
<i>the effect of which is like having your brains
smashed out by a slice of lemon</i>

471
00:36:54,300 --> 00:36:56,900
<i>wrapped round a large gold brick.</i>

472
00:37:01,600 --> 00:37:02,600
- Belgium.
- Belgium.

472
00:37:02,700 --> 00:37:04,400
Hold it one second.

473
00:37:05,500 --> 00:37:08,400
Hey, Ape-man, Earth dude...
I'm sorry, what's your name again?

474
00:37:08,500 --> 00:37:10,950
- Arthur.
- Right. Gorgeous.

475
00:37:11,050 --> 00:37:14,000
No hard feelings, okay?
Sorry to hear about your planet...

476
00:37:14,200 --> 00:37:15,200
- What's it called?
- Earth.

476
00:37:15,300 --> 00:37:17,100
Yeah, yeah. I liked Earth.
Got these boots there.

477
00:37:17,200 --> 00:37:19,350
But listen, don't mention it to the girl, okay?

478
00:37:19,450 --> 00:37:23,200
Because if you do, I'll pull your
spleen out through your throat.

479
00:37:23,300 --> 00:37:26,200
- All right. Thanks, buddy.
- Okay, okay.

480
00:37:26,300 --> 00:37:29,300
Good stuff. Like those jammies.

481
00:37:30,650 --> 00:37:35,150
Hey, hey, Zaphod,
what's with the two-head thing?

482
00:37:35,900 --> 00:37:39,900
Oh, yeah. Apparently, you can't be
president with a whole brain.

483
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:41,700
It's crazy.

484
00:37:41,800 --> 00:37:44,200
- Oh, so you carved it up?
- Yes.

485
00:37:44,300 --> 00:37:47,700
Some parts of my personality weren't
exactly what you'd call... presidential.

485
00:37:47,800 --> 00:37:49,200
- You know what I mean?
- No, no, no!

486
00:37:49,300 --> 00:37:50,500
No, you know what I'm talking about.

487
00:37:54,150 --> 00:37:56,750
<i>Your tea is ready.</i>

488
00:38:08,850 --> 00:38:12,450
I suppose I should've said it resembles tea.

489
00:38:13,550 --> 00:38:16,000
So, two heads is what does it for a girl?

490
00:38:16,400 --> 00:38:18,750
I mean, if I'd had two heads,
or, I don't know, three...

491
00:38:18,850 --> 00:38:20,950
Or your own spaceship.

492
00:38:22,100 --> 00:38:23,800
Anything else he's got two of?

493
00:38:23,900 --> 00:38:26,400
Come on, Arthur, don't be like that.

494
00:38:26,550 --> 00:38:30,700
What am I supposed to be like?
You know. Green? Bleeping?

495
00:38:30,800 --> 00:38:33,600
I can fold my eyelids inside out if you like.

496
00:38:33,750 --> 00:38:37,000
Okay, look. Do you see this?

497
00:38:37,650 --> 00:38:41,650
This detects what you're craving
and makes it for you.

498
00:38:41,750 --> 00:38:44,050
<i>Enjoy your doughnut.</i>

499
00:38:47,750 --> 00:38:49,500
Do you see this?

500
00:38:52,900 --> 00:38:59,400
This toasts bread while you're slicing it.

501
00:39:00,350 --> 00:39:05,250
We're on a spaceship, Arthur! In space!

502
00:39:05,350 --> 00:39:08,250
- I told you I wanted to get away.
- To Madagascar.

503
00:39:08,350 --> 00:39:14,550
That was... some sort of test.
And I failed.

504
00:39:14,650 --> 00:39:18,150
- How badly does it hurt?
- It doesn't feel great.

505
00:39:18,250 --> 00:39:20,250
No, I mean your chin.

506
00:39:21,350 --> 00:39:23,500
- I might have an aspirin.
- Right.

508
00:39:26,900 --> 00:39:28,900
Hey!

509
00:39:30,700 --> 00:39:35,800
Tricia... Trillian, sorry.
There's something I have to tell you.

510
00:39:35,900 --> 00:39:39,200
- Please, don't.
- Showtime, Trill!

511
00:39:45,950 --> 00:39:48,500
I'm going to set up.
Buttons aren't toys.

512
00:39:48,600 --> 00:39:50,250
Buttons aren't toys.

513
00:39:50,350 --> 00:39:53,400
Anyway, when I saw
what I'm about to show you,

514
00:39:53,500 --> 00:39:58,150
that's when I realized why I had to do
what I did to my brain.

515
00:39:58,300 --> 00:40:01,400
I think, it's all a little...

516
00:40:02,200 --> 00:40:03,250
shaky.

517
00:40:06,300 --> 00:40:09,450
I've seen it. It's rubbish.

518
00:40:13,050 --> 00:40:15,250
<i>Many millions of years ago,</i>

519
00:40:15,350 --> 00:40:18,750
<i>a race of hyper intelligent,
pan-dimensional beings</i>

520
00:40:18,850 --> 00:40:22,750
<i>got so fed up with the constant
bickering about the meaning of life,</i>

521
00:40:22,850 --> 00:40:25,700
<i>that they commissioned
two of their brightest and best</i>

522
00:40:25,800 --> 00:40:29,250
<i>to design and build
a stupendous super-computer</i>

523
00:40:29,350 --> 00:40:33,700
<i>to calculate the answer to life,
the universe and everything.</i>

524
00:40:33,800 --> 00:40:36,800
O' Deep Thought,

525
00:40:36,900 --> 00:40:41,150
we want you to tell us the answer.

526
00:40:41,250 --> 00:40:43,500
<i>The answer to what?</i>

527
00:40:43,600 --> 00:40:48,200
The answer to life,
the universe, everything.

528
00:40:48,300 --> 00:40:52,350
We'd really like an answer.
Something simple.

529
00:40:52,450 --> 00:40:54,700
<i>I'd have to think about that.</i>

530
00:40:55,200 --> 00:41:02,050
Return to this place in exactly
7.5 million years.

531
00:41:02,150 --> 00:41:04,200
- Is it finished?
- No, no, no, there's more. There's more.

531
00:41:04,700 --> 00:41:05,800
They go back.

532
00:41:05,900 --> 00:41:11,000
- What, 7.5 million years later?
- That's right, they do.

533
00:41:27,700 --> 00:41:32,000
- Deep Thought, do you have--
- An answer for you?

534
00:41:33,250 --> 00:41:35,000
Yes, but you're not gonna like it.

535
00:41:35,900 --> 00:41:38,900
- It doesn't matter. We must know it.
- All right.

536
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:41,950
The answer to the ultimate question...

537
00:41:43,900 --> 00:41:47,550
of life, the universe and everything...

538
00:41:49,200 --> 00:41:50,300
is...

539
00:41:57,150 --> 00:41:58,700
42.

540
00:41:58,850 --> 00:42:01,550
Yeah? What?

541
00:42:01,650 --> 00:42:04,150
42!

542
00:42:04,250 --> 00:42:08,450
Yes, yes, I thought it over
quite thoroughly. It is. It's 42.

543
00:42:08,550 --> 00:42:11,800
It would've been simpler, of course,
to have known what the actual question was.

544
00:42:11,900 --> 00:42:16,750
But it was the question.
The ultimate question. Of everything!

545
00:42:16,850 --> 00:42:18,750
That's not a question.

546
00:42:18,850 --> 00:42:22,200
Only when you know the question
will you know what the answer means.

547
00:42:22,300 --> 00:42:27,300
- Give us the ultimate question then.
- I can't. But there is one who can.

548
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:31,350
A computer that will calculate
the ultimate question.

549
00:42:31,450 --> 00:42:34,050
A computer of such infinite complexity,

550
00:42:34,150 --> 00:42:38,200
that life itself will form part
of its operational matrix.

551
00:42:38,350 --> 00:42:42,450
And you yourselves shall take on new,
more primitive forms,

552
00:42:42,550 --> 00:42:48,300
and go down into the computer to
navigate its 10-million-year program.

553
00:42:48,400 --> 00:42:52,100
I shall design this computer for you,
and it shall be called...

554
00:42:57,600 --> 00:43:01,000
- That's it?
- That's it.

555
00:43:01,300 --> 00:43:02,500
You're looking for the ultimate question.

555
00:43:02,600 --> 00:43:03,700
- Yep.
- You?

555
00:43:03,800 --> 00:43:05,150
- Me.
- Why?

556
00:43:05,250 --> 00:43:08,000
No, I tried that. Why? 42. Doesn't work.

557
00:43:08,100 --> 00:43:10,950
- Let's get it ready, baby.
- Why...

558
00:43:11,050 --> 00:43:13,000
do you wanna know the ultimate question?

559
00:43:13,100 --> 00:43:17,250
Oh, well, partly the curiosity,
partly a sense of adventure,

560
00:43:17,400 --> 00:43:20,750
but mostly I think
it's for the fame and the money.

561
00:43:20,850 --> 00:43:23,000
You're President of the Galaxy, aren't you?

562
00:43:23,100 --> 00:43:25,000
- That's right, Arman.
- Arthur.

563
00:43:25,100 --> 00:43:27,400
Whatever. Presidential fame is temporary.

564
00:43:27,500 --> 00:43:31,300
I find the question, that's permanent. It sticks.

565
00:43:31,400 --> 00:43:33,900
Plus, everyone thinks you're deep. Win-win.

566
00:43:34,650 --> 00:43:39,350
We just hit that button and... Bam!
...we're at Magrathea, I think.

567
00:43:39,450 --> 00:43:42,650
I mean, I don't know, we've hit it twice
and we're still not there, but anyway...

568
00:43:42,750 --> 00:43:45,150
- You in?
- Always.

569
00:43:45,250 --> 00:43:48,000
- All right!
- I want to get off.

570
00:43:48,100 --> 00:43:51,550
- Sorry, what exactly are we doing?
- This!

571
00:43:55,800 --> 00:43:59,500
<i>The Infinite Improbability Drive
is a wonderful new method</i>

572
00:43:59,600 --> 00:44:02,400
<i>of crossing interstellar distances
in a few seconds,</i>

573
00:44:02,500 --> 00:44:05,700
<i>without all that tedious
mucking about in hyperspace.</i>

574
00:44:05,800 --> 00:44:09,000
<i>As the Improbability Drive
reaches infinite improbability,</i>

575
00:44:09,100 --> 00:44:13,100
<i>it passes through every conceivable
point in every conceivable universe</i>

576
00:44:13,200 --> 00:44:14,950
<i>almost simultaneously.</i>

577
00:44:15,050 --> 00:44:17,000
<i>In other words, you're never sure
where you'll end up,</i>

578
00:44:17,100 --> 00:44:19,800
<i>or even what species you'll be
when you get there.</i>

579
00:44:19,900 --> 00:44:22,850
<i>It's therefore important
to dress accordingly.</i>

580
00:44:22,950 --> 00:44:27,300
<i>The Infinite Improbability Drive was invented
following research into finite improbability,</i>

581
00:44:27,450 --> 00:44:29,500
<i>which was often used
to break the ice at parties</i>

582
00:44:29,600 --> 00:44:32,500
<i>by making all the molecules
in the hostess' undergarments</i>

583
00:44:32,600 --> 00:44:34,900
<i>leap simultaneously one foot to the left</i>

584
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:37,600
<i>in accordance with
the theory of indeterminacy.</i>

585
00:44:37,700 --> 00:44:41,250
<i>Many respectable physicists said they
weren't going stand for that sort of thing,</i>

586
00:44:41,350 --> 00:44:43,450
<i>partly because it was
a debased of science,</i>

587
00:44:43,550 --> 00:44:47,500
<i>but mostly because they didn't get
invited to those sort of parties.</i>

588
00:44:57,800 --> 00:45:01,250
Wow! Is this gonna happen
every time we hit that button?

589
00:45:01,350 --> 00:45:03,250
Very probably, yes.

590
00:45:04,350 --> 00:45:06,300
I think the Earthman's about to be sick.

591
00:45:06,400 --> 00:45:09,250
Whoa, whoa! Do it in the trashcan,
ape-man. This ship's brand new.

592
00:45:09,700 --> 00:45:12,000
Aw, Come on!

593
00:45:12,100 --> 00:45:14,600
We have normality.

594
00:45:14,750 --> 00:45:16,400
Did it work? Are we there?

595
00:45:18,250 --> 00:45:22,350
Yeah. We're here. Magrathea!

596
00:45:22,450 --> 00:45:24,200
- I don't think so. Eddie...
- Magrathea!

597
00:45:24,500 --> 00:45:26,250
What planet are we looking at?

598
00:45:26,350 --> 00:45:28,150
<i>I'm checking for you.</i>

599
00:45:28,250 --> 00:45:33,250
Did you just pluck one of my hairs?
Off my head?

600
00:45:34,050 --> 00:45:36,900
<i>Thank you so much for waiting.
I'm sorry to disappoint you gang,</i>

601
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:39,050
<i>but this is not Magrathea.</i>

602
00:45:39,200 --> 00:45:42,900
<i>We are currently in orbit around
the planet Viltvodle Six.</i>

603
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:46,750
Humma Kavula!

604
00:45:46,850 --> 00:45:51,800
Magrathea's gonna have to wait.
I got a score to settle on this planet.

605
00:45:52,650 --> 00:45:56,850
Humma Kavula!

606
00:45:59,800 --> 00:46:04,050
<i>In the beginning,
the universe was created.</i>

607
00:46:04,150 --> 00:46:08,950
<i>This made a lot of people very angry,
and has been widely regarded as a bad move.</i>

608
00:46:11,100 --> 00:46:14,350
<i>Many races believed that
it was created by some sort of god.</i>

609
00:46:14,450 --> 00:46:17,900
<i>Though the Jatravartid people
of Viltvodle Six firmly believed</i>

610
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:22,050
<i>that the entire universe was, in fact,
sneezed out of the nose of a being</i>

611
00:46:22,150 --> 00:46:24,950
<i>called the Great Green Arkleseizure.</i>

612
00:46:25,050 --> 00:46:26,700
Humma Kavula!

613
00:46:26,800 --> 00:46:29,100
<i>The Jatravartids,
who lived in perpetual fear</i>

614
00:46:29,200 --> 00:46:32,650
<i>of the time they called the
'Coming of the Great White Handkerchief',</i>

615
00:46:32,750 --> 00:46:36,550
<i>were small blue creatures
with more than 50 arms each.</i>

616
00:46:36,650 --> 00:46:39,200
<i>They were unique in being
the only race in history</i>

617
00:46:39,300 --> 00:46:43,000
<i>to have invented the aerosol deodorant
before the wheel.</i>

618
00:46:44,900 --> 00:46:46,900
Mr. President!

619
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:48,700
Hey, all right. How you doin'? All right.

620
00:46:48,800 --> 00:46:51,000
Hey, what have we here? I love it!

621
00:46:56,350 --> 00:46:58,450
Hey, I love you. Fantastic!

622
00:46:58,550 --> 00:47:01,150
You guys related? Don't go changing. Keep up!

623
00:47:01,250 --> 00:47:03,350
Arthur, I want a drink.

624
00:47:03,450 --> 00:47:07,600
I think I've been here before.
Have I been here before?

625
00:47:11,200 --> 00:47:13,250
Ixxie!

626
00:47:13,400 --> 00:47:16,350
- I've been here before.
- Humma Kavula!

627
00:47:16,450 --> 00:47:18,000
Come on.

628
00:47:18,300 --> 00:47:21,100
Tricia! Tricia!

628
00:47:34,300 --> 00:47:45,000
♪ Thy Handkerchief to bring us back to Thee ♪

629
00:47:49,500 --> 00:47:51,200
Hello, Humma.

630
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:54,200
Please, join us. Sit down.

630
00:47:54,800 --> 00:47:57,400
Hey, good to see you. Thanks. All right.

631
00:47:57,500 --> 00:47:59,600
The handkerchief is coming beloveds.

632
00:47:59,750 --> 00:48:05,600
Let us pray the Almighty will exhale
a breath of compassion on us all.

633
00:48:07,250 --> 00:48:11,200
So that's Humma Kavula.
I thought he was just swearing.

634
00:48:11,900 --> 00:48:16,200
We lift our noses, clogged and unblown,

635
00:48:16,300 --> 00:48:18,400
in reverence to you.

636
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:25,100
Send the handkerchief, O' Blessed One,
so that it may wipe us clean.

637
00:48:25,200 --> 00:48:30,900
We ask this and all things
in Thy precious and alliterative name.

638
00:48:39,850 --> 00:48:41,700
Bless you.

639
00:48:42,150 --> 00:48:44,500
Where're we going? We're in here?

640
00:48:44,600 --> 00:48:48,400
All right, I like it. It's big,
it's gold, it's fancy. Fancy pants.

641
00:48:48,500 --> 00:48:52,050
Zaphod Beeblebrox,
our infamous President.

642
00:48:52,150 --> 00:48:54,850
What brings you to our humble planet?

643
00:48:54,950 --> 00:48:57,000
Oh, I think you know why I'm here.

644
00:48:57,100 --> 00:48:58,900
No, I don't think I do.

645
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:05,650
Oh, I think you think you don't.
But we both know you do.

646
00:49:05,750 --> 00:49:07,500
Eloquent as always, Zaphod.

647
00:49:07,600 --> 00:49:11,450
Your ability to articulate
never ceases to amaze.

648
00:49:11,550 --> 00:49:14,600
That's funny. During the campaign, Humma,

649
00:49:14,700 --> 00:49:17,100
when you were my opponent
running against me,

650
00:49:17,200 --> 00:49:19,500
you said I was stupid.

651
00:49:38,850 --> 00:49:44,200
The election is ancient history, Zaphod, but...

